Chris Mueller for The Wall Street Journal Colin Meloy, lead singer and songwriter for indie rock band the Decemberists, his wife, illustrator Carson Ellis, and their 5-year-old son live right across from Portland's 5,000-acre Forest Park. These woods infuse the lyrics of many of the Decemberists' songs; "The King Is Dead," their sixth album featuring a silhouette of the forest designed by Ms. Ellis, debuted at the top spot on the Billboard 200 chart in February. The couple's first book, "Wildwood," named after the longest of Forest Park's trails, made the top 10 of the New York Times children's chapter book best-seller list last week, and has been optioned for a film by Laika, the animation studio that made "Coraline." In the book, a girl's baby brother is kidnapped by crows and taken to the "Impassable Wilderness." Although the couple live amongst a handful of homes not far from downtown Portland, it feels they are in the wild because of all the trees. "A lot of what I've written has been inspired by living in this house, being freed of a neighborhood, with the wilderness across the street," said Mr. Meloy, 36, who has a full beard and black-rimmed glasses. Ms. Ellis, 35, with red hair and sharp cheekbones, half-jokingly refers to their location as survivalist's paradise—a place where they could live on their own vegetables and fruit, drink water from the creeks and hunt meat in a post-apocalyptic scenario. Built in 1928, their 2,000-square-foot, two-bedroom, two-bath house is like many of Ms. Ellis's illustrations: retro, picture-book sweet with lots of character. It's set on a sloping lawn with a vegetable garden out back and a kid's bicycle and rubber boots on the front stoop. The couple has kept the interior sparse; the furniture is a mixture of IKEA sofas, wooden tables they either made themselves or had custom made and sheepskin rugs. In the living room is a black Eames chair, a set of cubbies with a vinyl record collection and a record player. The room for their son Hank has a 4-foot wide sculpture of a moon, made by artist Jesse Durost. In back of the house, past an outdoor patio with a long wooden table and stairs up to the garden flanked by plum trees, is a detached garage that the couple turned into dual studios. Mr. Meloy calls his a man cave, stocking it with a leather sofa, a wine rack loaded with vintages from Côtes du Rhônes and lots of musical instruments. On his desk are two wood blocks, one saying "First Thought" and the other saying "Best Thought"—Allen Ginsberg's governing principle that Mr. Meloy uses to keep himself writing. Upstairs, Ms. Ellis's office is cozier, with a sloped roof, skylights and a long wood table she made for her drawing space. She has worked on a number of children's books, including those by authors Lemony Snicket and Trenton Lee Stewart. They collaborate: Mr. Meloy always has a say about the Decemberists' album covers, and he often runs lyrics by his wife. Working together on "Wildwood" meant lots of crossover between upstairs and downstairs. Mr. Meloy would plan the plot; Ms. Ellis would run her preliminary drawings past him. Sometimes their physical proximity can be a problem. Mr. Meloy likes "weird ambient" music, Pandora radio or silence when he works; Ms. Ellis at times blasts Kanye West. "I get a lot of old man texts that say 'turn that rap down'," said Ms. Ellis. Mr. Meloy grew up in Helena, Mont., and spent summers with his uncle in Oregon. He started college at the University of Oregon but transferred to the University of Montana to study writing, where he met Ms. Ellis, who was in Missoula getting a degree in painting. After graduation, Mr. Meloy returned to Oregon in 1999, playing at first on his own at small bars in Portland and then starting the Decemberists with a group of friends in 2000. The band released its first album "5 Songs" in 2001, followed by "Her Majesty" in 2003 and its breakthrough album "Picaresque" in 2005. Mr. Meloy and Ms. Ellis first lived in a house in the city's Northeast section. But after many walks in Forest Park, they decided they wanted to be nearer to the woods and farther from people. He found the changing seasons in their forest walks inspiring. They bought their current house, already renovated, in 2008 for $475,000. A four-bedroom, three-bath home twice the size nearby is for sale for $499,000. The house is smaller than they'd wanted, and limited storage means Mr. Meloy has to rein in his penchant for accumulation, particularly of kitchen gadgets (waffle maker, panini maker, rice maker). Still, they have no plans to move. "We like to keep our footprint small," said Mr. Meloy. Write to Nancy Keates at nancy.keates@wsj.com Email
